Managing director Karen Smart stepped down just as politicians and unions met bosses to discuss the "concerning" situation. Thousands again waited in long queues as staff shortages ruined the start of the Easter holidays for many. Lines started forming from 6am at London's Heathrow Airport while people queued from before 5am at Manchester where mayor Andy Burnham suggested police and fire services could be drafted in to help. EasyJet cancelled dozens of flights and is expected to do so again in coming days due to absences which it said were double normal levels due to Covid. Paul Charles, of travel consultancy The PC Agency, said: "It's a nightmare situation for airlines and airports."